Scientists have found a way to discover related stars
Astrophysics from the University of California at Santa Cruz studied turbulent agitation and its impact on chemical homogeneity in star clusters.
It is expected that the opening of specialists will allow to look among the stars related, that is, emerged from the same cluster.
The results of their research were published in Nature magazine, and briefly they can be found on the university website.
The reason for the same chemical composition of the nearby stars is turbulent mixing in the clouds of gas, preceding the formation of stars.
Even if the born star then leaves the star cluster, according to its chemical composition, it is possible to determine the place of its birth and the region of formation of native stars.
Scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to differences in its chemical content from those of relatives in the cluster.
The results of modeling conducted by astrophysics show that such differences should not appear.
In their research specialists with the help of supercomputer modeled two streams of interstellar gas, which together formed a cloud.
This object for several million years under the action of its own gravity is transformed into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
Scientists added paint-marks to the initial gas flows and established that due to the rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud, a high degree of chemical homogeneity is achieved.
According to astrophysics, their research proves that it is possible to look for native star by chemical composition, as well as to determine possible regions of education of such objects.
