Remembering the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keit Allison and John Lewis proposed a bill according to which the organization of trade unions is protected as civil law.
"Where the trade unions are, there are middle-class jobs," says Ellison, a democrat from Minnesota, who is the co-chairman of the Congress of the Progressive Faction.
That is why I am proud to present the Act on Enlargement of Workers' Rights along with the symbol of the Civil Rights Movement John Lewis.
This innovative bill will give employees the same legal opportunities in discriminating the organization of trade unions as in other forms of discrimination, stopping the forces of opponents of the trade unions
Amendment of the Law on Regulation of Labour Relations in such a way as to allow workers facing discrimination for participation in the organization of trade unions to seek justice in civil courts - and to receive compensation for damages and penalties - a reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is certainly not a radical initiative - at least according to American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and co-authors of the bill offer is to remember a very American thought.
Despite the attacks that the trade unions have been subjected to in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the country - the Americans once supported the countries around the world to adopt, extend and respect labor rights.
There was a time that still remembers millions of Americans when this country simultaneously defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of press and the right to organization.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas McArtur and his assistants helped the country adopt a constitution designed to ensure that the paramilitary Hideki Todz so was replaced by democracy.
Being fully aware that the workers and their trade unions play a role in the formation of a new Japan, they included a text that directly admitted that "the right of workers to the organization, to negotiations, and to the collective action is guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhauser and his assistants helped the Germans to write a constitution that guaranteed that the fascism of Adolf Hitler was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that employees will need to be organized and heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that openly stated: "The right to form associations in order to protect and improve labor and economic conditions will be guaranteed to each person and every profession or field of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to infringe on this right will not have legal force; measures aimed at these purposes will be recognized as illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was the chairman of the International Commission for Human Rights, which compiled the World Declaration on Human Rights, which in 1948 will be adopted by the United Nations as a worldwide agreement, Roosevelt and the compilers included the guarantee that "everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions to protect his interests."
By the generation of Americans took as a proper basis provision that labor rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries on how to create civil and democratic societies, the Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions - and that this trade union participates as an equal partner in collective negotiations with corporations and government institutions - should be protected.
Now that these rights are attacked in America, it is wise to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and to hear their voices in a free and open society.
As the Venerable Martin Luther King said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement has not undermined the forces of the nation, but increased them.
Raising the living level of millions, trade unions miraculously created a market for industry and raised a whole nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers how it should be.
The official recognition of labor rights as human rights - and the expansion of the protection of civil rights in order to prevent discrimination against the organization of trade unions - has long been overdue.
Keith Allison and John Lewis revive the ideals that historically expanded America and made a promise of democracy a reality.
The judge temporarily blocks the law that could close all abortion clinics in Louisiana
In the U.S., the federal judge temporarily blocked the introduction of the law of Louisiana, which his supporters say that he is likely to close all five abortion clinics in the state.
According to this measure, which was signed by the governor Louisiana Bobby Ginadl in June and was to come into force on September 1, doctors who make abortions would be obliged to have the authority to receive patients in the hospital within a radius of 30 miles from their practice.
However, the judge's decision means that at the moment doctors can continue to make legal abortions, continuing to seek such powers.
"The plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally, continuing their actions to obtain authority," Judge John deGrawells wrote in his decision.
The hearing will be scheduled for a month at which the judge will make a more permanent decision according to this law.
The defenders of the right to abortion gladly met this decision, the last in a series of decisions against similar measures, saying that it will give doctors more time to receive hospital powers.
"Today's decision guarantees that Louisiana women will be protected from an insidious law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights," said Nancy Northap, President and head of the Reproductive Rights Center, who filed a lawsuit to stop the law on behalf of three of the five state clinics.
It was not immediately obvious whether the decision to doctors from two clinics, who did not act as plaintiffs in this case, and also filed an application for the procedure of admission.
Louisiana is part of 11 states that have adopted such laws, and the courts have recently recognized such measures as unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
The key parts of the Texas law, which would close most of the remaining clinics in this state, were blocked by the federal judge on Friday.
Fighters for the right to abortion together with the American College of Midwives and Gynecologs and the American Medical Association say that the laws on the authority of admission impose restrictions on doctors that are not necessary in terms of medicine.
Opponents of abortion argue that such measures are aimed at protecting women's health, although some also noted their positive effect in the closure of clinics.
Only one doctor who makes abortions in Louisiana has the authority to receive in the hospital, said the Center for Reproductive Rights.
If all other doctors in the state will be forced to stop performing this procedure, this doctor, afraid for his safety, would stop performing this procedure, the group said.
Criticizing this decision, Louisiana officials said that they will not punish doctors making abortions while their applications for the authority of acceptance are waiting for the decision.
