In other words, the fight for the buyer will develop between companies operating under the common laws of the industry.
On the other hand, Kasyanov notes, Russian producers are able to meet 50% of the internal needs of compatriots under all articles.
And in this situation, trade networks will have to "grow" the share of Russian goods to half of the range.
In this regard, there are increasing fears that low-quality products will be received on the counters.
Perhaps under the guise of produced in Russia will be supplied foreign products with broken labels," the expert adds.
The negative effect of the introduction of quotas will feel large trading networks, especially those that are more profitable to cooperate with importers.
It is logical that in such a situation will suffer and foreign suppliers themselves, as the demand for their products will decrease.
Litvinenko does not rule out that the law on quotas for domestic goods can affect consumers.
The fact is that some products of Russian production may yield to the quality of imported analogues, while stores will be able to inject prices for the second, as a deficit of goods.
The idea of import substitution forgotten in the early 2000s was again discussed by economists in February this year due to the continued devaluation of the ruble.
Now, against the background of difficult relations with the West, the issue of abandonment of imported products becomes even more relevant.
The law is designed to oblige retailers in the formation of orders to suppliers to take into account domestic manufacturers.
Then we will go much faster and more confidently along the way of import substitution, and the system of planning production for the necessary types of products will be created in a shorter time," - said the deputy Oleg Nilov.
Particularly effective mechanism of quotas will be for those agricultural sectors, where the potential is particularly high, for example, in the dairy industry, where the share of imports was 25%.
Our farmers are really able to completely cover the shelves of Russian stores.
In addition, a powerful impulse can get and meat production.
As is known, the largest share of imports is maintained by beef - from 30% to 35%.
It turns out that 65-70% still account for Russian products," says Kasyanov.
Experts believe that the introduction of quotas for domestic products will contribute to import substitution and can speed up this process.
However, in itself, this initiative will not lead to import substitution, because this requires a set of measures, I am sure Litvinenko.
In any case, 50% of the goods sold under this initiative can still be brought from abroad, and therefore, there will be no full import substitution, but significant steps in this direction will be done.
In addition, it is not enough to set quotas, it is necessary to establish production of domestic products in the country in order to fulfill these quotas.
These quotas will provide just such guarantees," the expert states.
Untimely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more
Angelina Jolie and her brother James published a video of their late mother, who died of ovary cancer in 2007.
Women who are in the countryside of Australia face a higher risk of death from ovarian cancer than those living in cities.
The researchers analyzed the maps of the disease of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with "the ovarian cancer" in 2005, discovering that only 35 percent lived five years after the diagnosis was put.
Leading researcher Susan Jordan from the Institute for Medical Research QIMR Berghofer said that the probability of death during the study is 20 percent higher for those who live in the regions and remote areas of the state than those living in urban areas.
NOWIS OF THE RESPOSE: New Medications can slow down lung cancer and ovarian cancer
The researchers traced the medical path of women in seven years.
Doctor Jordan said that the age of the woman at the time of diagnosis, type of ovarian cancer, the presence of current diseases and socioeconomic status also influenced the likelihood of survival.
Older women and those who had cancer in a later stage at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
For those who lived in regions or remote areas of the state, the likelihood of dying during the study was 20 percent higher than for those who lived in urban areas.
Although the study was not intended to determine why women living outside cities are more likely to die of ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that the untimely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment are possible factors.
"This disease is best treated by surgeons specializing in gynecological oncology, and they are mainly in big cities," she said.
Despite the improvement in the quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of the distance, she suggested that an increase in the number of services on the road, which will allow specialists to treat women closer to home, and support programs for people undergoing treatment far from their home, can help.
Doctor Jordan said that regardless of geographical position, the study revealed that the long life expectancy among women with ovarian cancer was rare, emphasizing the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
A study funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer can be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young mother from the Golden Bank of Elish Niv said that she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
