Genetic disturbance is often misintrocerated
Britanka reported that she spent many years, thinking that she would die after a wrong diagnosis.
Carin Rogers spent most of her teenage years, thinking that she had only a few years left to live after she was diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had a disease Sharko-Marie-Tuta (SMT) - a group of hereditary disorders that lead to damage to nerves outside the brain and spine.
The CMT UK Charity Organization reported that the wrong diagnosis is a frequent problem among people with ShMT, because so little is known about this state.
Approximately 23,000 people in the UK have a SchMT, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, uncertain gait and pressed toes.
Patients may feel numbness or pain, and the condition is not cured and progresses, which means that the symptoms are intensified over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from the attack of Friedreich (AF) - a condition that was very bad for which the forecast was very bad.
Rogers thought she would be chained to a wheelchair by the time she would be 18 and die before she was 30.
The mother of two children, who is now 51, said: "A child I knew that I can't do what others.
I fell every day, and everything went for me more time.
I could never skate or skateboard with other children, and I was mocked a lot at school because I went and ran.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several operations, to release the Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she looked into the medical card when her doctor left the room, and it was written that she had AF.
"I felt guilty because I put my nose on where I shouldn't, and that's why I didn't tell anyone, but I returned home, found information about it in the library and wrote to the Association of the AF," she said.
When I got the information in response, I was shocked and experienced the most terrible panic that was possible.
I thought I would be in a wheelchair in 18 and I would die before I was 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in this interval.
I went through it alone and I planned my own funeral.
She said that by the time she was 17, she realized that her ability to walk did not deteriorate as much as she thought, and asked her doctor about it.
He just got up, hugged me and said, "My dear, I don't think you have this disease, because you would have been in a wheelchair."
I think you have something that poses a much smaller threat to life.
After several genetic examinations she found ShMT.
"When he explained what the ShMT was, I thought I had pulled out a lucky ticket," she said.
The Charity Organization of the ShMT of Great Britain announced a month of information about the ShMT to try to draw attention to this disease.
The tax burden on the entrepreneurs of the Washington zone is growing as the economy recovers
The recovering economy means more customers, more sales and new jobs.
This also means higher taxes.
The state and local tax accounts for companies across the country increased moderately last year, when the economic recovery accelerated, according to a new study published last week, and the company in the Washington zone is no exception.
Companies in the district, Maryland and Virginia totaled $27.6 billion in the state treasury and at the local level in financial 2013, by 3.8 percent more than $26.6 billion collected in 2012.
The tax burden on the state and local business increased by 4.3 percent last year to $671 billion, compared to 3.9 percent a year earlier, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after the years going on, when the accounts were reduced, in 2009 and 2010.
The taxes charged by the state increased faster, 4.3 percent than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study conducted by a firm providing professional services, Ernst &amp; Young and the State Taxation Center, a tax policy group.
More than half of the tax revenues in the district, 56 percent, account for business taxes, while 36% of the tax revenues of Maryland account for the firms.
Virginia, with 28 percent, brings the lowest amount of tax revenues, proportionally, from entrepreneurs.
To a large extent, the growth of tax revenues is caused by a return to the previous level of the value of real estate in companies, the researchers say, which raised property taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three years in a row, when the growth was less than 1 percent.
While a large proportion of these revenues fall on large states such as California, New York and Texas, it seems that the same is happening in the Washington zone.
Companies in the district, Maryland and Virginia have collected $10 billion of state and local property taxes last year, $9.6 billion more than in 2012 - an increase of 4.2 percent compared to the previous year.
However, the observed return of the value of real estate has no similar effect on the growth of tax revenues in the state and at the local level in Maryland, where property taxes barely exceed one-fifth of tax accounts of companies.
Companies Virginia and the District of Columbia pay about half of the tax accounts on the state and at the local level in the form of real estate taxes.
"What's going on in Maryland is that such a large part of their real estate, especially the tax base around the District of Columbia, belongs to either the government or a non-profit organization that does not pay real estate taxes," said Douglas Lindholm, Executive Director of the State Taxation Center.
Thus, Maryland has to rely much more, for example, on income taxes to pay for the same services that are in other states.
The recent growth of tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully explained by the restoration of the real estate market.
The revenues of entrepreneurs also seem to be amended, according to these data.
Companies in the region declared corporate income tax at $2.3 billion, $2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland collected $1 billion corporate income tax revenues, the most in the region.
Although the trends are directed in one direction, the tax burden of entrepreneurs at the local level does not increase at the same speed in all three areas.
The growth level in the District of Columbia was at the same level as the average in the country, 4.3 percent, while the growth in Maryland was significantly faster, 4.9 percent.
Only in Virginia there was an increase in tax revenues below the average, equal to 4.1 percent.
In Virginia there was the lowest corporate income tax of three jurisdictions (each of which is the same corporate rate), equal to 6 percent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 percent, while in the district it is relatively high - 9.975 percent.
A similar study of the US Chamber of Commerce earlier this year showed that in Virginia there are lower taxes for entrepreneurs in the state and at the local level and, in general, a more favorable climate in terms of taxes for entrepreneurs than in Maryland.
The circle was not evaluated in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is experiencing competitive pressure from its neighbor from the south.
North Carolina recently signed a legislative act reducing the corporate rate this year from 6.9% to 6%, as well as in Virginia, and the rate will fall to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to achieve tax revenues targets next year, this law could bring the income tax rate for entrepreneurs even up to 3 percent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small business in the Washington zone seems to feel better and thus pays more taxes on the state and at the local level, according to a recent study.
Taxes for entrepreneurs paid in the form of individual income tax by small business owners - a transitional structure, which is arranged by most small firms - in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia increased by 20 percent last year to $2.4 billion, with a much higher rate than taxes for entrepreneurs in general.
Researchers say that the trend and increase in revenues from business taxes across the country are likely to remain this year, when the VAT in the state governments and at the local level, which increased by 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
