MPs proposed to speed up the entry into force of the law on personal data
In case of success of the initiative, these Russians will not be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015
The State Duma introduced a draft law providing for the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law on personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is located in the basis of legislative activities of the lower chamber.
It was compiled by Duma deputies Vadim Dengin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Yevgeny Fedorov (United Russia), Vladimir Parakhin (Just Russia) and Alexander Yushchenko (CPRF).
Such a change, according to the authors of the initiative, will contribute to more operative and effective provision of the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation to the safety of personal data and compliance with the secret of correspondence in information and telecommunication networks.
The law, the entry into force of which is in a hurry parliamentarians, obliges to store on the territory of the Russian Federation personal data of Russians processed via the Internet.
It also makes obligatory recording, systematization, accumulation, storage, clarification and extraction of personal data of citizens of the Russian Federation, in databases located on the territory of Russia, as well as indication of information about the location of such databases.
In addition, the law gives Roskomnadzor the right on the basis of a court decision to restrict access to information processed in violation of the legislation of the Russian Federation in the field of personal data.
The law also proposes the creation of so-called "black lists" of offender sites - automated information system "Registers of violators of rights of subjects of personal data."
This law was passed by the State Duma in summer.
The authors of the bill were Andrei Lugovoi and Vadim Dengin from the LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko from the CPRF.
Dengin and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current bill on the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who do not have data centers in the Russian Federation, will have to pay for rent
Commenting on the bill submitted to the State Duma today, the first deputy head of the Duma committee for information policy Leonid Levin said that he sees no problems for the postponement of the date of entry into force of the law on personal data protection.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own personal data stores in the territory of the Russian Federation, will be able to rent them, for example, "Rostelecom," who repeatedly said that they are ready to provide their servers for rent and already provides their servers, Mail Group, Western companies that now already provide their servers."
"In addition, there are several independent data centers ready to cooperate in this field," he added.
"If companies decide to comply with the law and continue to work on the territory of the Russian Federation, I see no problems - they will receive technological opportunities for accommodation," Levin summed up.
Controversial bill
Immediately after the publication of the draft law, the Russian Association of Electronic Communications expressed concern that if the bill is adopted, Russians will no longer be able to use many global Internet services.
In particular, we are talking about the services of online booking of tickets and hotels.
According to the association, "the bill deprives the subjects of personal data - citizens of the Russian Federation the right to dispose of their own data imperatively determining that their recording, systematization, etc. should be provided only in databases located on the territory of the Russian Federation."
The statement of the RAEC emphasizes that a more effective measure would be to create a mechanism for informing the user about where the recording is carried out, the systematization of his personal data.
In this case, he will be able to choose which territory will be carried out these actions.
The adoption of such bills on "localization" of personal data in other countries has led to the departure of global services and significant economic losses.
