Saving certificate will make personal and irrevocable
The Ministry of Finance wants to ban the bearer's savings certificates, but will allow banks to make them an analogue of the irrevocable deposit.
The Ministry of Finance is preparing a bill that will prohibit the bearer's savings certificates.
Recently, this tool is gaining popularity, as rates here are higher than on bank deposits.
The fact is that the bearer's savings certificates do not fall into the deposit insurance system, and they are cheaper to the bank, because it is not necessary to make contributions to the Fund of the Deposit Insurance Agency (ASV).
The ingenuity of the situation is that this step is planned to be taken because of small and medium-sized banks that distribute such certificates, and will suffer from it Sberbank and the Bank of Moscow, which, according to ASV estimates, control 98% of the specialized market.
And the share of the Bank of Moscow, according to the agency, is about 3.5%.
The problem, explained in the ASV, is that the clients of a small bank who bought such a certificate, in the case of revocation of his license trying to get money in ASV.
Some depositors, not having sufficient financial literacy and buying savings certificates for bearers, may assume that their investments are insured.
The justified absence of insurance payments on these certificates in case of revocation of the license from the bank may lead to misunderstanding and social tension.
In the practice of the agency there were cases when the holders of bearers tried to recover insurance compensation through the court," - said in the ASV.
The problem, of course, is imaginary.
After all, no one will pay certificates to buyers anyway, because they have the law no right to reimbursement from the state.
If the case was that the instrument is not insured in the ACV, together with it would be banned and metal accounts, on which the funds of citizens are taken into account in the grams of one of the four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
After all, these accounts also do not fall into the deposit insurance system, but no one is bitten on their existence.
The point is most likely that the bearer certificates are a very convenient securities, which can actually act as a quasi-money.
At the same time, their movement is practically not subject to control: any client of the bank can buy a certificate, pass to any citizen, and before cashing such a certificate can change many owners.
It is not accidental that the bill stipulates that the savings certificate must be a personal security, which should be stored in the depository.
And in order to sweeten the pill to banks, such certificates are allowed to issue without the right of early repayment.
That is, an analog of irrevocable deposit, which has long dreamed bankers.
