Putin granted Russian citizenship to Ukrainian pentathlon
Russian President Vladimir Putin granted Russian citizenship to well-known Ukrainian athlete Anna Buryak.
The relevant decree was published on the Internet portal of legal information.
At the beginning of this year, the athlete moved to Russia for permanent residence and appealed to the Federation of modern pentathlon with a request to give her the opportunity to speak for the national team of the Russian Federation.
In 2013 she won two stages of the World Cup, won the silver medal of the European Championship in the individual championship and became the world champion in the mixed relay, which is one of the new types of program in this sport.
It holds back the leading position in the current season.
According to the rules to speak at the Olympic Games 2016 in Rio de Janeiro, she will need to get a special permission of the Olympic Committee of Ukraine.
Anna Buryak is not the first Ukrainian athlete who changed citizenship.
In July, Vladimir Putin decided to issue a Russian passport chess player Ekaterina Lagno - a native of Lviv, who is a two-time European champion (2005, 2008), the world in blitz (2010) and rapid chess (2014).
As part of the women's team of Ukraine, the athlete won the chess Olympiad in Turin (2006), the World Team Championship in Astana (2013) and the European Team Championship in Warsaw (2013).
TFR stopped investigation of the Tu-204 disaster in Vnukovo
The Investigative Committee of Russia (SKR) terminated the criminal case on the crash of the Tu-204 airline Red Wings.
It is reported by the press service of the agency.
The decision was made in connection with the death of the commander of the aircraft and the boarder.
Judicial expertise showed that the cause of the disaster was the increased speed of landing, failure to perform the crew of standard procedures at landing, as well as unintentional output of engines to increased turnover of direct thrust.
The plane Tu-204 of the airline Red Wings, which followed the flight Prague - Moscow, crashed on December 29, 2012 when landing at Moscow airport Vnukovo.
The aircraft rolled out over the runway and caught fire.
At the scene killed the commander of the aircraft, the second pilot and the boarder.
Two flight attendants were taken to medical institutions, where they later died from injuries.
Three more flight attendants, hospitalized with severe bodily injuries, were prolonged treatment.
In addition, a serious bodily damage was received by the driver of the car, moving at the time of the disaster on the Kiev highway.
There were no passengers on board the aircraft.
After the disaster, the Transport Prosecutor's Office conducted an inspection at Red Wings, during which numerous violations were identified.
In February 2013 the license of the airline was suspended.
The company resumed its work in the summer of 2013.
