Anger turned out to be the most universal and functional emotion of man
The hearty expression of the face is biologically universal for humanity, and each involved in its creation organ and muscle group is not accidental, but an additional means of expression of power and threat, the scientists of Australia and the United States have found out.
They told about their discoveries in the magazine Evolution and Human Behavior, and briefly about them can be found in the press release of the University of California in Santa Barbara.
The furious expression of the face - shifted and lowered eyebrows, stretched into a thin line of lips, bloated nostrils - are the same in all cultures, and make it even blind children from birth, never seen it, notes the leading author of the study Aaron Sell.
As part of a major research project dedicated to the nature of anger, scientists found out that this emotion arose for effective disputes during the conflict.
The more physical damage one person can cause another, the more opportunities he has to dictate his conditions, and he delivers it to the interlocutor with the help of anger.
Researchers have found evidence and other hypothesis: physically strong people are more angry and pass on to the application, consider themselves entitled to impose other unfavorable conditions for them, and also prefer force methods to resolve conflicts peaceful.
Repulsing that anger is primarily a "simple of bargaining," scientists have decided that the movements of each of the seven groups of muscles, creating an angry expression of the face, should represent an angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor - and thus make it possible to agree with his conditions to avoid conflict as soon as possible.
To check this hypothesis, researchers modeled the person on the computer, where each of the seven elements of an angry person was present or absent, and showed them to informants.
Although the lowered eyebrows or the chin put forward separately did not make the face evil, then the more powerful physically the participants of the study recognized the person, which was depicted with such traits of the person, unanimously.
The anger of man, as well as in animals, poses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of his own power, forcing to agree and obey.
A person blows up the nostrils and presses his lips with the same purpose as the frog that is inflated, or baboon, who demonstrates his fangs.
"The anger is launched by the refusal of the interlocutor to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes the form, which demonstrates the consequences of this refusal as effectively as possible.
But the most amazing thing is that none of the components of an angry face is arbitrary, they all express the same," said anthropologist John Tubi.
Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles to TV-radio company Crimea
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles from the federal budget of the autonomous non-profit organization "TV and Radio Company "Crimea" in 2014.
This is stated in the draft resolution of the government prepared by the department, which was acquainted with "Lenta.ru."
According to the explanatory note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be used to "cover the costs of creating conditions for large-scale information coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of modern information space in the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the purchase of equipment."
In particular, it is planned to re-equip the hardware and studio unit, video walls, central hardware and video-server.
It is also planned to purchase a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter.
In addition, from the allocated funds the company will pay for the use of fiber-optic communication line (FOCL) and repair of the energy system.
Subsidies will be provided within the federal budget provided for the Ministry of Communications.
The state-owned TV and radio broadcasting company "Crimea" was founded in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, the TV-Radio Company coverage is more than 75 percent of the peninsula.
In 2011 TV-Radio Company Krym received a digital broadcasting license.
